  "eprint": {
    "title": "Secure Massively Parallel Computation for Dishonest Majority",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Rex Fernando",
        "email": "rex1fernando@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Ilan Komargodski",
        "email": "komargodski@ntt-research",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Yanyi Liu",
        "email": "comyl2866@cornell",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Elaine Shi",
        "email": "edurunting@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "This work concerns secure protocols in the massively parallel computation (MPC)\nmodel, which is one of the most widely-accepted models for capturing the\nchallenges of writing protocols for the types of parallel computing clusters\nwhich have become commonplace today (MapReduce, Hadoop, Spark, etc.). Recently,\nthe work of Chan et al. (ITCS '20) initiated this study, giving a way to\ncompile any MPC protocol into a secure one in the common random string model,\nachieving the standard secure multi-party computation definition of security\nwith up to 1/3 of the parties being corrupt.\n\nWe are interested in achieving security for much more than 1/3 corruptions. To\nthat end, we give two compilers for MPC protocols, which assume a simple\npublic-key infrastructure, and achieve semi-honest security for all-but-one\ncorruptions. Our first compiler assumes hardness of the learning-with-errors\n(LWE) problem, and works for any MPC protocol with ``short'' output---that is,\nwhere the output of the protocol can fit into the storage space of one machine,\nfor instance protocols that output a trained machine learning model. Our second\ncompiler works for any MPC protocol (even ones with a long output, such as\nsorting) but assumes, in addition to LWE, indistinguishability obfuscation and a\ncircular secure variant of threshold FHE. Both protocols allow the attacker to\nchoose corrupted parties based on the trusted setup, an improvement over Chan et\nal., whose protocol requires that the CRS is chosen independently of the\nattacker's choices.",
    "keywords": [
      "secure computation",
      "massively parallel computation",
      "dishonest majority"
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
    "publication_info": "A minor revision of an IACR publication in TCC 2020",
    "last_updated": "2021-07-12",
    "license": "CC BY",
